/**
 * TODO (figures):
 *
 * z500_analogs.png:
 *   - Source: ERA5 reanalysis, daily 500hPa geopotential height (z500), winter DJF, 5° resolution.
 *   - Workflow: detrend the full series → compute daily seasonal climatology → subtract climatology
 *     to get anomalies → search analogs across different winters (exclude pairs less than 1 year apart)
 *     → keep the pair with smallest Euclidean distance.
 *   - Figure: two panels side by side, Northern Hemisphere maps with coastlines, panel titles = dates.
 *   - The pyanalogs package (available locally at ../analogs_package/pyanalogs/) can be used for
 *     the analog search and evaluation steps.
 *
 * sst_analogs.png:
 *   - Source: Kaplan SST v2, summer JJA.
 *   - Workflow: detrend → compute seasonal climatology → anomalies → same closest-pair logic as above.
 *   - Figure: same two-panel format with coastlines and dates as panel titles.
 *
 * Do NOT implement data download or figure generation inside the website build.
 * Place the generated figures in /public/assets/figures/ and uncomment the <img> tags below.
 */

import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import FigurePlaceholder from '../components/FigurePlaceholder.astro';
import { pdfLinks } from '../data/publicationLinks';

const p = pdfLinks;
---

<BaseLayout title="Research Themes" description="Paul Platzer — Research Themes">
  <h1>Research Themes</h1>

  <h2>Weather and Ocean Analogs</h2>

  <p>
    My first main research theme is weather/ocean analogs. It is a striking
    property of the atmospheric and ocean circulation that most observed patterns
    are recurring, i.e. similar patterns have been previously observed in the
    past and will be in the future. Here is an example of two similar patterns
    of 500mb geopotential height anomaly over the Northern Hemisphere occurring
    at remote times (data = ERA5 reanalysis).
  </p>

  <!-- TODO: replace with <img> once z500_analogs.png is generated -->
  <FigurePlaceholder
    filename="z500_analogs.png"
    alt="Two analog states of 500hPa geopotential height anomaly over the Northern Hemisphere, side by side with dates"
    caption="Example of two analog patterns of z500 anomaly (ERA5 reanalysis, DJF)"
  />

  <p>
    The large-scale atmospheric circulation on this part of the Earth is mostly
    driven by the jet-stream, which is a main driver of mid-latitude weather
    conditions. The jet stream always flows from West to East, but its particular
    configuration (shape and intensity) varies non-linearly (chaotically) and
    the latter forms meanders, caused by a meteorological phenomenon called
    &lsquo;Rossby waves&rsquo;. Most of the particular configurations of the
    jet-stream are recurring: almost every observed pattern will come back every
    few years.
  </p>

  <p>
    Here is another example of analogs using sea-surface temperature data
    (data = Kaplan SST v2).
  </p>

  <!-- TODO: replace with <img> once sst_analogs.png is generated -->
  <FigurePlaceholder
    filename="sst_analogs.png"
    alt="Two analog states of sea-surface temperature anomaly, side by side with dates"
    caption="Example of two analog patterns of SST anomaly (Kaplan SST v2, JJA)"
  />

  <p>I am interested in understanding the properties of analog-based statistical methods, covering several aspects:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      the properties of analog forecasts
      {p['Platzer2021a_JAS'] && <span class="pubref">(<a href={p['Platzer2021a_JAS']}>Platzer et al. 2021, JAS</a></span>}
      {p['PlatzerChapron2024'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['PlatzerChapron2024']}>Platzer &amp; Chapron 2024, STUOD proceedings</a>)</span>}
    </li>
    <li>
      the estimation of dimensions using analogs
      {p['Platzer2022_STUOD'] && <span class="pubref">(<a href={p['Platzer2022_STUOD']}>Platzer et al. 2022, STUOD Proceedings</a></span>}
      {p['PlatzerChapron2025'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['PlatzerChapron2025']}>Platzer &amp; Chapron 2025, JSP</a></span>}
      {p['Platzer2025_npj'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['Platzer2025_npj']}>Platzer et al. 2025, npj clim. and atm. sc.</a>)</span>}
    </li>
    <li>
      the estimation of uncertainties using analogs, especially predictability, and extreme events
      {p['Platzer2021a_JAS'] && <span class="pubref">(<a href={p['Platzer2021a_JAS']}>Platzer et al. 2021a, JAS</a></span>}
      {p['Platzer2021b_JAS'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['Platzer2021b_JAS']}>Platzer et al. 2021b, JAS</a></span>}
      {p['PlatzerChapron2024'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['PlatzerChapron2024']}>Platzer &amp; Chapron 2024, STUOD proceedings</a></span>}
      {p['Platzer2024_CP'] && <span class="pubref"> — <a href={p['Platzer2024_CP']}>Platzer et al. 2024, CP</a>)</span>}
    </li>
    <li>
      the optimization of analog methods, in particular the definition of analog distance, using
      gradient-descent-based algorithms
      {p['Platzer2025_MWR'] && <span class="pubref">(<a href={p['Platzer2025_MWR']}>Platzer et al. 2025, MWR</a>)</span>}
    </li>
    <li>
      the application of analog methods in relationship to AI algorithms such as AI weather
      forecasting (in preparation).
    </li>
  </ul>
</BaseLayout>
